{{Infobox person | name = Juliana R. Force | image = File:Juliana Force.jpg | signature = | caption = Force in 1940 | birth_name = Julianna Reiser | birth_date = {{birth date|1876|12|25}} | birth_place = [[Doylestown, Pennsylvania]], U.S. | death_date = {{Death date and age|1948|08|28|1876|12|25}} | death_place= [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S. | resting_place = | residence = New York City, New York, U.S. | nationality = American | occupation = Museum administrator | parents = | website = }}
'''Juliana R. Force''' (December 25, 1876{{spaced ndash}}August 28, 1948) was an American art museum administrator and director.
== Early life and education== Force was born '''Julianna Reiser''' in [[Doylestown, Pennsylvania]], on December 25, 1876.{{sfn|James|1971|p=646}} She became known as "Juliana".<ref name=Britannica> {{cite web |url= http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/213078/Juliana-Rieser-Force |title= Juliana Rieser Force |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year= 2014|website= www.britannica.com |publisher= Encyclopædia Britannica |accessdate=20 January 2014}}</ref> She was a twin and had seven other siblings besides her twin sister.{{sfn|James|1971|p=645}} Force's last name was spelled Reiser;{{sfn|James|1971|p=646}} she later changed the spelling to Rieser.{{sfn|James|1971|p=646}}{{sfn|Read|Witlieb|1992|p=162}} Her father was a [[grocer]]{{sfn|Goldsmith|2011|p=334}} and a [[hatter]]. {{sfn|James|1971|p=645}} The Rieser family moved to [[Hoboken, New Jersey]], in 1886.<ref name=Art_Historians>{{cite web |url= http://www.dictionaryofarthistorians.org/forcej.htm|title= Dictionary of Art Historians |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year= 2012 |website= Art Department |publisher= Duke University |accessdate= 20 January 2014}}</ref> As a child Force attended a Christian boarding school for girls.<ref name=Art_Historians/> For a short time in 1908 Force taught at a secretarial business school in [[Manhattan]], downtown New York City.{{sfn|Goldsmith|2011|p=334}} At the age of 35 Force married Willard Force, a dentist, then becoming known as "Juliana Rieser Force" or "Juliana Reiser Force" or "Juliana R. Force", which is sometimes shortened to "Juliana Force".{{sfn|Read|Witlieb|1992|p=162}}<ref name=Art_Historians/>
==Career== Force's first job was as the personal secretary of socialite [[Helen Hay Whitney|Helen Hay]] (wife of [[Payne Whitney]]).<ref name=Britannica/> At the age of 38 in 1914 she became the private secretary for Helen Hay's sister-in-law, [[Gertrude Vanderbilt Whitney]], a great-granddaughter of "Commodore" [[Cornelius Vanderbilt]] and eldest surviving daughter of [[Cornelius Vanderbilt II]]. Whitney, an art [[sculptress]] and [[art collector]], had inherited a Vanderbilt fortune.<ref name=Art_Historians/> Whitney gave as Force's first duty an assignment to help organize art exhibitions at the [[Colony Club]], an exclusive conservative social club for wealthy socialite women in New York City. Here Force showed off Whitney's art and a different kind of new unusual art by creative artists of a group called [[Ashcan School#Connection to "The Eight"|The Eight]]. Whitney was making a statement that all kinds of art, including different styles of art from new artists, should be represented to the public.<ref name=BrandNew>{{cite web |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1990/04/15/books/a-museum-for-the-brand-new.html |title= A Museum for the brand-new |last1= Robinson |first1= Roxana |last2= |first2= |year= 1990 |website= The New York Times Company |publisher= The New York Times newspaper |accessdate=20 January 2014}}</ref> Whitney was interested in displaying her collection of work as well as other art from modernist artists, especially living Americans.<ref name=Art_Historians/>
Whitney assigned Force in 1929 to contact the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] to prepare a plan for a gift of Whitney's collection. Whitney's art collection gift was to be displayed in a new wing, partly financed by her. The museum turned down the gift. Whitney then displayed her work in her own studios and galleries, that were under her name. Force managed these art enterprises and then in 1930 became director of the new [[Whitney Museum of American Art]] that developed from these art studio and gallery enterprises. Force was not trained as an art historian. She hired [[Lloyd Goodrich]], an art historian, to be curator of the Whitney Museum of American Art, best known throughout the United States for displaying new kinds and unusual styles of modern art from living artists. Force's passion for new styles of art and her organizational traits made her an administrative director of the nationally known art museum notable for twentieth and twenty-first century art.<ref name=Art_Historians/>
===Folk art=== Force initiated the first display of American [[folk art]] in a gallery in the United States, the "Early American Art" collection.{{sfn|Indych-López|2009|p=119 "The first public exhibition of American folk art was "Early American Art" held in February 1924 at Juliana Force's Whitney Studio Club, with objects selected by Henry Schnakenburg. It included naïve engravings, velvet paintings, portraits, cigar store Indians, a ship's figurehead, brass bootjack, and pewter serving bowls"}}{{sfn|Wertkin|2013|p=342 "Her endorsement of the field led to the first public exhibition of folk art in the United States."}} On February 9, 1924 she began a presentation of folk art in a Whitney gallery that she administered, intending to bring folk art attractiveness closer to the level of [[contemporary art]].{{sfn|Berman|1990|p=201 "Early American Art, which opened February 9, 1924, was the first exhibition of folk art held in America. Naïve engravings, paintings on velvet, portraits by untutored artists, a cigar store Indian, a ship's figurehead, a brass bootjack, and pewter serving bowls were put before the public as authentic works of art and vigorous evidence of a creative impulse in which Americans ought to take pride"}} Because of her passion for folk art, this initial display led to the first official public exhibition of folk art in a public showing presentation.{{sfn|Wertkin|2013|p=342 "Her endorsement of the field led to the first public exhibition of folk art in the United States."}}
Although her interactions with artists at the Whitney Studio Club inspired her to personally collect modern art,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pollock|first1=Lindsay|title=The Girl with the Gallery: Edith Gregor Halpert and the Making of the Modern Art Market|date=2007|publisher=PublicAffairs|location=New York|page=130}}</ref> her collections of nineteenth-century and older folk art and decorative arts were larger and more significant. Her Eighth Street apartment was decorated in a Victorian style, contrary to contemporary tastes, and her home at Barley Sheaf Farm in [[Doylestown, Pennsylvania|Doylestown]] was filled with her folk art collection.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Berman|first1=Avis|title=Rebels on Eighth Street: Juliana Force and the Whitney Museum of American Art|date=1990|publisher=Antheneum|location=New York|pages=145–147, 304–307}}</ref> Primarily acquired from rural antique dealers, her collection included portraits by early American [[Limner#United States|limners]], [[Theorem Stencil|theorem paintings]] on velvet, and eclectic objects like [[Cigar store Indian|cigar store Indians]] and toys.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Berman|first1=Avis|title=Rebels on Eighth Street: Juliana Force and the Whitney Museum of American Art|date=1990|publisher=Antheneum|location=New York|pages=145–147.}}</ref>
==Later life== Force became chair of the American Art Research Council<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/american-art-research-council-records-9397|title=A Finding Aid to the American Art Research Council records, 1935–1956|website=www.aaa.si.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-03-17}}</ref> in 1942. The United States government did a national tour show of German art in 1946 of [[war booty]].<ref name=Art_Historians/> Force shortly thereafter undertook a course of action to return the art to its rightful owner.<ref name=Art_Historians/>
The Whitney Museum of American Art directed by Force did art shows between 1946 and 1948 on [[Albert Pinkham Ryder]], [[Robert Feke]] and [[Winslow Homer]] to promote public awareness of these artists.<ref name=Art_Historians/>
==Death== Force died in New York City on August 28, 1948,{{sfn|Read|Witlieb|1992|p=162}} and buried at the Doylestown Cemetery in Pennsylvania.{{sfn|James|1971|p=646}} The museum held a memorial exhibition in her honor in 1949.<ref name=Art_Historians/>
==Personal life== Juliana Reiser married Willard Force in 1911. Her husband died in 1928, and they had no children.{{sfn|James|1971|p=645}}
